= Organic Lifecycle

#import "../lib/template.typ": aside

The DAO is a cell. Not a metaphor for decoration --- a structural observation. It has a membrane (membership), a metabolism (vaults), a genome (charter), and a set of behaviors it can express (proposals). It is born, it adapts, it reproduces, and it can die. The civilization mesh described earlier is a tissue made of these cells.

== Birth

A DAO begins with a charter, vaults, and a proposal set. These three elements are sufficient for life. A single founder with a vision and a wallet is a viable organism. The protocol imposes no minimum complexity.

As the organization grows, it acquires resources, expands its vocabulary of proposals, and recruits members. But the starting point can be as small as a single cell.

== Adaptation

A living organization changes its own rules. The charter can be amended. The proposal set can be expanded or contracted. Governance parameters can be tuned. The membership can be restructured entirely.

This self-referential capacity --- the ability of the rules to change the rules --- is what separates a living organization from a static contract. The safety rails ensure that adaptation is productive: high thresholds for existential changes, timing controls to prevent hasty mutations, floors that governance cannot lower below.

== Reproduction

A DAO creates Sub-DAOs. The offspring is a full cell --- same architecture, same capabilities, same lifecycle potential. It operates with genuine autonomy within the boundaries set by its parent.

The parent can relinquish control entirely, granting the offspring sovereignty. This emancipation is irreversible. The former department becomes a peer, free to reproduce, federate, and evolve independently.

== Metabolism

Resources flow through the mesh like nutrients through tissue. Deposits flow in without governance approval --- revenue, dues, grants. Withdrawals flow out through proposals --- salaries, funding, investment.

In hierarchical structures, metabolism extends across the organizational tree. Parents fund children downward. Children return revenue upward. Peers exchange laterally. The protocol provides the circulatory system; governance sets the metabolic policy.

== Death and Succession

A DAO can die deliberately. Migration creates a successor with a new governance model, transfers all vault contents --- including the ticker capability --- and archives the original. The identity persists; the organism is reborn.

This is not a failure mode. It is how organizations evolve past the limits of their original design. A tribe that outgrows board governance migrates to a stake-weighted model. The ticker resolves to the successor. The history is preserved. Life continues.

== The Civilizational Substrate

The DAO mesh is not just an organizational layer. It is the substrate on which finance and technology emerge in Frontier.

Finance requires custody, budgeting, revenue routing, and accountability. These are vault operations governed by proposals. Technology requires infrastructure ownership, capability delegation, and upgrade authority. These are capability vault operations governed by proposals. Both rest on the same primitive.

A tribal economy is a mesh of DAOs metabolizing resources. A trade network is a federation of DAOs exchanging value through their treasuries. A technology commons is a DAO holding infrastructure capabilities in its vault and governing access through proposals.

Every charter amendment, every treasury allocation, every Sub-DAO creation is recorded permanently on-chain. Future players can study the governance patterns of extinct organizations, trace the evolution of successful ones, and learn from the decisions that shaped Frontier's trajectory.

The protocol provides the cells. Players provide the intent. Civilization is what grows.
